comment.narrative:
The CCM Secretariat facilitated the CCM selection for 2020-21 carried out with participation of 144 individuals and legal entities: 56% (87) is key affected population representatives: SW, MSM, PWID and Women LHIV, 18.7% (27) - local CSOs on healthcare issues, 2.7% (4 academic sector), 9.7% (14 local NGOs for PLHIV), 7.6% (11 international organizations); as a result, 20 candidates were selected to CCM from different sectors.
• The update of the Resolution of the Prime Minister of the Republic of Kazakhstan On the Country Coordinating Committee on Work with International Organizations on HIV-issues and Tuberculosis was launched; UNDP recruited a national consultant who assisted in amending the Resolution of the Government of the Republic of Kazakhstan (currently - the Resolution of the Prime Minister of the Republic of Kazakhstan), following the results of the CCM elections in 2018;
• The CCM Oversight Committee for HIV/TB grants was selected and established comprising 5 national and international experts with diseases, management skills and representative of key affected population, thus complying with the Global Fund requirements and being fully functional; 
• 21 projects/organizations were attended during the CCM oversight visits to identify gaps and progress in implementation of national HIV and TB programmes, on sustainability of ongoing Global fund projects as well as programmes earlier funded by the Global Fund; the respective reports are published on the CCM website;
• 175 decision makers and programme implementing partners during the 4 CCM meetings were ensured awareness on MSM, OST, HIV and TB in different KAP, state social orders for local NGOs program and their focus on increasing state funding for HIV/AIDS prevention programs; Ensured equal participation of the representatives of key populations (PLHIV, MSM, PWID, SW, women living with HIV, ex-TB patients), non-governmental, academic and private sector representatives, as a result, the following decisions were approved: 1) the Minister of Healthcare of the Republic of Kazakhstan was reappointed and approved as the CCM Chair following the results of the CCM selection; 2) the CCM transition plan from international to domestic funding on TB component was developed and approved; 3) the CCM Country Dialogue Plan on preparation of the new TB funding proposal was designed and implemented; 4) the CCM Funding Request on TB component for 2020-2022 was developed and approved; as a result, a new Grant Agreement between CCM and the Ministry of Healthcare and Global Fund on TB component for US $8,054,000 dollars was signed; 5) approval of results of the work of the grant Principal Recipients; 6) implementation and expansion of OST Program approved.
• 60 participants who are CCM members and non-CCM members improved their knowledge and skills on CCM role and functions, development of funding requests, monitoring and evaluation instruments to practice and improve the quality of programmes implementation;
20 Newly selected CCM members are trained and able to take part in the decision making
CCM Oversight Committee is established and CCM Oversight function fully implemented 
100% of CCM activities were fully implemented
